[{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-14#0","metadata":{"content":"**Precedence with multiple attestations:** `invalid` dominates — if any attestation for the skill carries a signature that FAILS verification against a *registered* key, the skill's verdict is `invalid` regardless of other valid attestations (a forged signature is a red flag, not noise; and since `attestations.json` is publisher-controlled, an attacker poisoning it can only block the publisher's own skills). Otherwise: any valid, in-window attestation → `attested`; else any expired one → `expired`; else `unattested`. Attestations from unregistered attesters are ignored for precedence (they are unverifiable, verdict input UNKNOWN-ATTESTER only as diagnostics).","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-14","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 4. Runtime behavior"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-mcpwasm-static-mcp-1#0","metadata":{"content":"mcpwasm is the reference implementation: a sandboxed runtime for third-party MCP tools (untrusted tool code inside QuickJS-wasm on Cloudflare Workers), plus a gateway that turns any static site publishing `llms.txt` with executable skills into an MCP server.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-mcpwasm-static-mcp-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-47#1","metadata":{"content":"workflows the MCP does — in **~3 tool calls vs. the MCP's 6–7**, with **validation preserved** (unlike a naive RES","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-47","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-72#0","metadata":{"content":"**Trade-off:** It adds one round-trip per new domain. Agents SHOULD cache negative responses (404) to avoid repeated probes.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-72","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-1-skill-entry-9#0","metadata":{"content":"The key is deliberately **not** `sha256`: the core RFC already uses `sha256` (inline and in `/.well-known/agent-skills/index.json`) for the hash of the fetched `SKILL.md`. The two keys MAY appear on the same skill line and verify different files; runtimes MUST NOT conflate them.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-1-skill-entry-9","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.1 Skill entry"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-14#0","metadata":{"content":"A publisher MAY additionally ship a **search snapshot**: a pre-built, hash-pinned full-text index over its own content, so that skills can offer real search over a purely static site — no backend API required. Declared with one origin-level line in `llms.txt` (place it **before** the `## Skills` section — some conformant parsers fold trailing non-list lines into the last skill entry):","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-14","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.4 Origin memory: search snapshots"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-tl-dr-1#0","metadata":{"content":"Añade una sección `## Skills` a tu `llms.txt`. Cada entrada es un link a un `SKILL.md` remoto. Los agentes descubren skills en el mismo documento que ya leen para entender tu sitio. Sin servidor, sin proceso persistente, sin autenticación extra.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-tl-dr-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: TL;DR"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-54#0","metadata":{"content":"**Reference implementation.** `scripts/generate.py` signs with ed25519 (deterministic, RFC 8032); `scripts/verify_signatures.py` verifies each `SKILL.md` against the published public key.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-54","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 4.6 Signing and authenticity (resolves Open Question 4)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-2-existing-alternatives-require-infras-8#0","metadata":{"content":"The reference implementation for this RFC (`img.automators.work`) is a **Cloudflare Pages static site**. It cannot run an MCP server. It *can* serve a text file.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-2-existing-alternatives-require-infras-8","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.2 Existing alternatives require infrastructure most sites do not have"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-6-open-questions-25#0","metadata":{"content":"1. Should `tool`/`tool_sha256` live only in `/.well-known/agent-skills/index.json` instead of inline, keeping the inline comment single-key? (This draft chooses inline for zero-infrastructure parity; feedback welcome.) 2. Artifact size limit (the reference implementation truncates fetched bodies at 4 KB for `fetchOrigin` but does not yet cap artifact size). 3. A declared capability list per skill (e.g. `\"capabilities\":[\"fetchOrigin\"]`) so runtimes can surface least-privilege prompts before loading. 4. WASM artifacts as a second artifact type (`tool.wasm` + WIT-style interface) for non-JS publishers.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-6-open-questions-25","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 6. Open questions"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-14#0","metadata":{"content":"List the skills the demo site publishes:","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-14","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-1-motivation-2#0","metadata":{"content":"This extension adds the third ring: **attestations** — signed, expiring statements by named reviewers that a specific artifact, on a specific origin, was reviewed and endorsed. Two design commitments inherited from the donor PoC:","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-1-motivation-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-2-relationship-to-agents-txt-the-actio-37#0","metadata":{"content":"**Concrete interoperability (implemented).** The reference generator emits `/.well-known/agent-skills/index.json` as a **superset of the agentskills.io `discovery/0.2.0` schema**: every skill carries the fields that schema expects (`name`, `type: \"skill-md\"`, `description`, `url`, `digest: \"sha256:…\"`) *plus* this RFC's extensions (`version`, `license`, `homepage`, raw `sha256`, ed25519 `signature`, and a top-level `signing_key`). One file therefore satisfies both an `agents.txt`/agentskills.io consumer (discovery + integrity) and a Tier-2 consumer (authenticity) — the publisher maintains no second artifact. The redundant `digest` (prefixed form) and `sha256` (raw hex) fields are kept in parallel so existing consumers that read raw `sha256` are not broken.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-2-relationship-to-agents-txt-the-actio-37","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.2 Relationship to `agents.txt` (the action layer)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-2-existing-alternatives-require-infras-5#0","metadata":{"content":"| Mechanism | What it requires | Works for a static blog? | |---|---|---| | **MCP** | A persistent server process, transport layer, endpoint | **No** | | **A2A** | A persistent server process, agent-to-agent protocol | **No** | | **`/.well-known/skills/`** | Static file serving only | **Yes, but only one skill** |","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-2-existing-alternatives-require-infras-5","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.2 Existing alternatives require infrastructure most sites do not have"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-4-why-structured-over-prose-12#0","metadata":{"content":"`llms.txt` is free-form markdown. A site could write skill discovery as prose:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-4-why-structured-over-prose-12","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.4 Why structured over prose"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-security-model-honest-18#1","metadata":{"content":"ed or corrupt content is rejected and not cached. - **Origin-scoped fetch.** `host.fetchOrigin` only fetches the single al","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-security-model-honest-18","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Security model (honest)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-8-open-questions-88#1","metadata":{"content":"is more natural for git-hosted skill bundles. 4. **Signature scheme beyond `sha256`.** Resolved (§4.6): a two-tier model — `sha256` for integrity (required when declared), plus optional ed25519 signatures over an offline key","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-8-open-questions-88","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 8. Open Questions"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-16#0","metadata":{"content":"Call `server_time` (async tool that calls `host.fetchOrigin(\"/api/time\")` on the allowed origin):","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-16","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-2-optional-inline-metadata-20#0","metadata":{"content":"The only recognized key is `version`. It is a human-readable hint for quick identification, not a security mechanism. Agents that do not understand the comment MUST ignore it.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-2-optional-inline-metadata-20","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.2 Optional inline metadata"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-50#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Tier 1 — Integrity (`sha256`).** MUST be verified when declared. Cheap, offline, no key management. Already specified in §2.2 and §4.3. - **Tier 2 — Authenticity (signature).** OPTIONAL. The publisher signs each `SKILL.md` with a private key kept **offline, off the web server**. The public key is published (e.g., `/.well-known/agent-skills/signing-key.pub`, and/or a `signing_key` field in `index.json`). Agents verify the signature over the skill content.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-50","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 4.6 Signing and authenticity (resolves Open Question 4)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-65#0","metadata":{"content":"**Why it matters:** DNS resolution is often faster than HTTP and can be cached at the resolver. The agent can discover the `llms.txt` URL *before* making any HTTP request, allowing it to preload skills or show them to the user at the exact moment the domain is mentioned.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-65","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-2-recommended-agent-behavior-non-norma-75#0","metadata":{"content":"**Cache strategy:** - `llms.txt`: cache per HTTP `Cache-Control` (typically short TTL, e.g., 5 minutes). - Negative 404: cache for 24 hours to avoid repeated probes. - `SKILL.md`: cache per HTTP `Cache-Control` (can be long, e.g., immutable).","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-2-recommended-agent-behavior-non-norma-75","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.2 Recommended Agent Behavior (Non-Normative)"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-architecture-8#0","metadata":{"content":"- `host.mjs` — synchronous `ToolHost` (sync tools, `host.callInternal` capability). - `host-async.mjs` — `AsyncToolHost` (async handlers, `host.fetchOrigin` capability, resource hardening). - `mcp-core.mjs` / `mcp-core-async.mjs` — JSON-RPC 2.0 MCP core (transport-agnostic). - `worker.mjs` — PoC MCP server (sync host, inline tools). - `worker-spike.mjs` — async spike (fetchHome/fetchEvil). - `worker-gateway.mjs` + `llmstxt-parse.mjs` — the gateway.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-architecture-8","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Architecture"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-quick-start-12#0","metadata":{"content":"`npm run gateway` is documented as-is from `package.json`; it builds the gateway worker and runs `mf-gateway.mjs` against the real deployed demo site.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-quick-start-12","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Quick start"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-1-two-ecosystems-that-do-not-talk-to-e-3#0","metadata":{"content":"The result: a site describes itself in `llms.txt`, and it publishes a `SKILL.md` somewhere, but there is **no standardized way** for the site to say *\"here is the skill you need to work with me\"* — and no standardized way for an agent to discover it.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-1-two-ecosystems-that-do-not-talk-to-e-3","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.1 Two ecosystems that do not talk to each other"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-5#0","metadata":{"content":"1. The **publication format** for executable skills (publisher side). 2. The **minimum requirements** for a runtime that chooses to execute them (consumer side).","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-5","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-17#0","metadata":{"content":"- PoC sync host: `https://toolhost-mcp.rckflr.workers.dev` (POST `/mcp`). - Demo publisher: `https://llmstxt-demo-site.rckflr.workers.dev/llms.txt` (the root path returns 404 by design — only specific routes are served).","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-17","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-17#0","metadata":{"content":"Verification MUST be independently computable from static files: fetch `attestations.json`, verify Ed25519 (available in Workers/browsers via WebCrypto) against the registry. No callbacks to any service.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-17","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 4. Runtime behavior"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-architecture-7#1","metadata":{"content":"n; any other origin throws inside the sandbox. 5. The gateway maps MCP `to","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-architecture-7","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Architecture"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-85#0","metadata":{"content":"**Implications:** - Skill discovery is not triggered by implicit references in user prompts. - Even Mechanism D (the `/llms.txt` convention probe) only works if the agent is already navigating the domain, not when the domain is merely mentioned in text. - This suggests that either: - Agents need a pre-action step: \"before answering any task involving a domain, probe its `llms.txt`\", or - User instructions need an explicit signal (e.g., \"use the skill at...\") to trigger discovery.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-85","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.4 Discovery from User Instructions"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-2-the-artifact-tool-js-11#0","metadata":{"content":"The artifact is a single JavaScript file that registers exactly one tool:","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-2-the-artifact-tool-js-11","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.2 The artifact (`tool.js`)"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-4-security-considerations-21#1","metadata":{"content":"e's credentials, other tenants, or other origins. - **Residual risks:** a compromised publisher origin can still publish a *correctly hashed* malicious artifact (garbage in, verified garbage out); `fetch","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-4-security-considerations-21","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 4. Security considerations"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-61#0","metadata":{"content":"Every HTTP response from the domain MAY include a `Link` header pointing to `llms.txt`:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-61","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-5-reference-implementation-24#0","metadata":{"content":"The gateway demonstrates: discovery from `llms.txt`, per-skill SHA-256 verification with exclusion on mismatch, sandboxed execution (QuickJS-wasm) with async handlers in per-skill contexts, origin-scoped `fetchOrigin` including POST write skills (a real order decrementing D1 stock), deterministic gas interruption of infinite loops, and end-to-end consumption by an unmodified MCP client (headless Claude configured with only the gateway URL).","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-5-reference-implementation-24","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 5. Reference implementation"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-1-two-ecosystems-that-do-not-talk-to-e-4#0","metadata":{"content":"**Concrete example:** `img.automators.work` serves an SVG placeholder image API. It has a `llms.txt` that documents the API. It also has a `SKILL.md` that teaches agents how to build placeholder URLs. But an agent that reads `llms.txt` has **no signal** that the `SKILL.md` exists. The user must know the URL in advance.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-1-two-ecosystems-that-do-not-talk-to-e-4","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.1 Two ecosystems that do not talk to each other"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-architecture-7#0","metadata":{"content":"1. A publisher site ships `/llms.txt` plus per-skill `tool.js` and `SKILL.md` files. `llms.txt` lists each executable skill with a SHA-256 of its `tool.js`. 2. On each request the gateway downloads `llms.txt`, parses the executable skills, downloads each `tool.js`, verifies SHA-256, and loads the verified ones into a fresh `AsyncToolHost` scoped to that origin. 3. Tool code runs inside QuickJS-wasm. It can only call `host.fetchOrigin(path, opts?)` (`opts`: `{method: \"GET\"|\"POST\", body?: string ≤16 KB, contentType?}` — write skills go through POST), which is async from the host side but synchronous-looking inside the sandbox (QuickJS asyncify suspends/resumes the wasm stack). 4. The host fetches only the allowed origin; any other origin throws inside the sandbox. 5.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-architecture-7","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Architecture"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-30#0","metadata":{"content":"The core idea here — *a Markdown manifest hosted at your domain that agents read, with no server process* — is being arrived at independently by others, which is a useful signal that the pattern is sound.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-30","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.1 Relationship to adjacent protocols"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-rfc-publishing-agent-skills-through-llms-0#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Status:** Draft (v0.8) - **Date:** 2026-06-02 - **Author:** automators.work - **Depends on:** [llmstxt.org](https://llmstxt.org/) spec, [Agent Skills](https://agentskills.io) (`SKILL.md`) - **Reference implementation:** [img.automators.work](https://img.automators.work)","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-rfc-publishing-agent-skills-through-llms-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: RFC: Publishing Agent Skills through `llms.txt`"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-80#0","metadata":{"content":"**Implications:** - A publisher cannot assume that publishing a skill guarantees the agent will use it as written. - The RFC defines *what* to publish and *where* to find it, but not *how* the runtime must enforce execution. - This is intentionally out of scope (Section 7), but it is a real, observable gap that future work should address.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-80","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.3 Observed Execution Gap"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-16#0","metadata":{"content":"When a supported snapshot is declared, verified, and loaded, the runtime injects one additional capability into that origin's skills:","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-16","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.4 Origin memory: search snapshots"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-3-reviewer-registry-trust-anchor-10#0","metadata":{"content":"Verification requires knowing reviewers' public keys. The registry is **runtime-side configuration**, not publisher data — the publisher hosting the keys that vouch for the publisher would be circular:","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-3-reviewer-registry-trust-anchor-10","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 3. Reviewer registry (trust anchor)"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-why-6#0","metadata":{"content":"- The tool runs in a separate QuickJS-wasm context with no host globals beyond what the host predefines (`registerTool`, `host`). No `fetch`, no `process`, no disk, no secrets. - The platform secret (e.g. a Stripe key) stays on the host side. The tool can only ask the host to perform a *named* internal action via `host.callInternal` (sync host) or a scoped `host.fetchOrigin` (async host). The host decides what is allowed. - The tool's `tool.js` is content-addressed by SHA-256; the gateway refuses to load it if the hash declared in `llms.txt` does not match the bytes it fetched. - Resource limits bound what a malicious/buggy tool can do: memory cap, stack cap, and a wall-clock interrupt deadline per call.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-why-6","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Why"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-6-why-this-is-worth-doing-86#1","metadata":{"content":"cument, in one fetch, with no additional probing. - **Multi-skill support.** A single domain can publish skills for different use cases (e.g., read-only queries, authenticated writes, admin operations) as separate entrie","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-6-why-this-is-worth-doing-86","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 6. Why This Is Worth Doing"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-77#0","metadata":{"content":"**Empirical evidence from DemoShop:** In a live test, an agent: 1. Discovered the `cart-add` skill via `llms.txt`. 2. Downloaded and read `SKILL.md`, which specified a Python `urllib` pattern with explicit headers and error handling. 3. Ignored the prescribed pattern and used its generic PowerShell `Invoke-WebRequest` tool instead.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-77","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.3 Observed Execution Gap"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-7-non-goals-87#0","metadata":{"content":"- Replacing local skill filesystems or marketplaces — both remain valid distribution modes. - Defining a new skill format — this RFC reuses the Agent Skills `SKILL.md` spec as-is. - Mandating skill *execution* behavior — that is the agent runtime's responsibility. - Replacing MCP or A2A for complex, stateful integrations — this RFC targets the simpler, static-hosting case.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-7-non-goals-87","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 7. Non-Goals"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-9-reference-implementation-92#0","metadata":{"content":"- [`/llms.txt`](https://img.automators.work/llms.txt) — contains a `## Skills` section - [`/skills/placeholder/SKILL.md`](https://img.automators.work/skills/placeholder/SKILL.md) — the skill itself - [`/docs/rfc-skills-in-llms-txt.md`](https://img.automators.work/docs/rfc-skills-in-llms-txt.md) — this document - [`/scripts/parse_llms_txt_skills.py`](https://img.automators.work/scripts/parse_llms_txt_skills.py) — reference parser - [`/scripts/validate.py`](https://img.automators.work/scripts/validate.py) — validator - [`/schema/llms-txt-skills.schema.json`](https://img.automators.work/schema/llms-txt-skills.schema.json) — JSON schema","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-9-reference-implementation-92","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 9. Reference Implementation"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-1-skill-entry-7#0","metadata":{"content":"An executable skill is declared with two additional keys in the skill entry's JSON comment:","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-1-skill-entry-7","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.1 Skill entry"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-58#0","metadata":{"content":"**What this RFC adds, even today:** when an agent does encounter a site — via user instruction, a URL in context, or a tool result — a `## Skills` section gives it an unambiguous, machine-readable signal that purpose-built skills are available. That is more than any site can currently express through `llms.txt` alone.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-58","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5. On Agent-Side Discovery Triggers"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-4-security-considerations-21#0","metadata":{"content":"- **What the hash buys:** whoever can edit the site cannot silently swap artifact bytes out from under a cached/pinned hash; and a runtime never executes bytes it did not verify. It does **not** authenticate the publisher — for that, compose with the signature scheme of core RFC §4.6 (signing `llms.txt` transitively pins every declared `tool_sha256`, alongside the core RFC's `sha256` for the prose). - **What the sandbox buys:** a malicious artifact can, at worst, compute and call its own origin — the same things any visitor's browser can already do to that origin. It cannot reach the runtime's credentials, other tenants, or other origins.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-4-security-considerations-21","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 4. Security considerations"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-5-security-considerations-18#1","metadata":{"content":"— short validity windows are the honest stopgap. - **Expiry is a feature.** An expired attestation returning to `unattested` is the freshness layer doing its job: endorsements ro","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-5-security-considerations-18","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 5. Security considerations"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-mcpwasm-static-mcp-0#0","metadata":{"content":"**Static MCP: your tools are files, not servers.** Tools are published as static, hash-verified content and executed sandboxed on demand. What static site hosting did to web servers — \"don't run Apache, publish HTML\" — this does to MCP servers: don't run an MCP server, publish files. The publisher needs zero infrastructure; the MCP server is materialized per request from those files and evaporates after responding (ephemeral instance, durable definition).","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-mcpwasm-static-mcp-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-security-model-honest-18#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Tool-host isolation.** Tool code runs in a QuickJS-wasm context separate from the Worker's JS. It sees only `registerTool`, `host`, and what the host prelude defines. No `fetch`, no `process`, no globals leak by default. - **Secrets stay outside the sandbox.** In the sync PoC, the platform secret is read from `env.STRIPE_SECRET` on the host side and is never exposed to tool code — the tool can only call named internal methods. In the gateway, there is no platform secret; the only capability is `host.fetchOrigin`. - **SHA-256 content addressing.** The gateway downloads `tool.js` and verifies it against the `tool_sha256` declared in `llms.txt` before loading. Mismatched or corrupt content is rejected and not cached.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-security-model-honest-18","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Security model (honest)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-2-recommended-agent-behavior-non-norma-74#0","metadata":{"content":"**Key principle:** The user opt-in (step 6) remains mandatory. Even with automatic discovery, agents MUST NOT auto-install skills without explicit approval.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-2-recommended-agent-behavior-non-norma-74","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.2 Recommended Agent Behavior (Non-Normative)"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-15#0","metadata":{"content":"| Key | Requirement | Meaning | |---|---|---| | `snapshot` | REQUIRED | Same-origin path to the snapshot file. | | `snapshot_sha256` | REQUIRED | Lowercase hex SHA-256 of the exact bytes served at `snapshot`. (Named to avoid the core RFC's `sha256`, same rationale as `tool_sha256`.) | | `format` | REQUIRED | Snapshot format identifier. Runtimes MUST ignore a `skills-memory` line whose format they do not support (skills load normally; the capability is simply absent). This draft registers one format: `minimemory-okf-v1` (BM25-only index exported by [minimemory](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/minimemory)'s `WasmOkfIndex`; no embeddings, no query-time model needed). |","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-15","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.4 Origin memory: search snapshots"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-mcpwasm-static-mcp-2#0","metadata":{"content":"Think \"php-wasm, but for MCP tools\": the platform owner embeds the host, loads `tool.js` files, and each tool runs isolated in a QuickJS WebAssembly sandbox. The only bridge from the sandbox to the platform's internals is an explicit capability the host injects. No capability, no access.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-mcpwasm-static-mcp-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-27#0","metadata":{"content":"*Example:* A documentation site teaches agents to quote specific sections when answering questions about its content.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-27","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.4 Two primary use cases"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-62#0","metadata":{"content":"**Why it matters:** When the agent makes its *first* request to the domain (e.g., loading the homepage or calling an API endpoint), it receives this header for free. No extra round-trip is needed to probe for `llms.txt`. The agent parses the header, fetches `llms.txt`, and discovers skills before the user even asks.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-62","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-7-changelog-26#1","metadata":{"content":"ished as a static snapshot (`minimemory-okf-v1`). - **v0.3 (2026-07-02):** Lessons from a realistic field test (D1-backed bookstore + unmodified MCP client): explicit sandbox-globals note (ECMAScript only, no WHATWG APIs); `fetchOrigin` extended with optional `{method, body, contentType}` (GET/POST only) enabling write skills; resource budgets SHOULD be deterministic gas, not wall-clock (frozen clocks in Workers); MCP exposure MUST wrap non-object results in `structuredConten","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-7-changelog-26","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 7. Changelog"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-1-two-ecosystems-that-do-not-talk-to-e-2#0","metadata":{"content":"`llms.txt` tells LLMs what a domain *is*. Agent Skills (`SKILL.md`) tell an agent *how to use* that domain. Both exist. Neither knows about the other.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-1-two-ecosystems-that-do-not-talk-to-e-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.1 Two ecosystems that do not talk to each other"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-2-optional-inline-metadata-21#0","metadata":{"content":"**For integrity verification and full metadata** (sha256, license, cost estimates, requirements), agents SHOULD fetch `/.well-known/agent-skills/index.json` if available. That document is the canonical metadata source. The `## Skills` entry is the discovery pointer; `.well-known` is the verification and metadata layer.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-2-optional-inline-metadata-21","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.2 Optional inline metadata"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-68#0","metadata":{"content":"**Why it matters:** It is more discoverable by HTML parsers than `rel=\"alternate\"` (which some agents ignore). It also signals to developers inspecting the page source that the site exposes agent-facing resources.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-68","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-55#0","metadata":{"content":"This RFC defines the *publishing* side of the protocol. It does not mandate when or how agents decide to read `llms.txt`.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-55","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5. On Agent-Side Discovery Triggers"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-4-why-structured-over-prose-13#0","metadata":{"content":"This works for an LLM reading the document. It does not work for:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-4-why-structured-over-prose-13","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.4 Why structured over prose"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-33#0","metadata":{"content":"**General principle.** As more agent-facing Markdown conventions appear (`llms.txt`, `## Skills`, `AUTH.md`, `.well-known/*`), the risk is fragmentation. This RFC's position: `llms.txt` is the natural **co-located discovery layer** — an agent already reading it to understand a domain should find capability and pointer information there in one fetch, with `.well-known` and protocol-specific manifests (like `AUTH.md`) as the verification and specialized layers beneath it.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-33","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.1 Relationship to adjacent protocols"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-2-3-publication-8#0","metadata":{"content":"Attestations are published by the origin as a static JSON array at:","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-2-3-publication-8","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 2.3 Publication"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-3-the-well-known-convention-is-limited-9#0","metadata":{"content":"The emerging `/.well-known/skills/default/skill.md` convention (proposed by Cloudflare, adopted by Mintlify) works when: - The agent knows the domain in advance. - The agent is configured to probe `.well-known` paths.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-3-the-well-known-convention-is-limited-9","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.3 The well-known convention is limited"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-3#0","metadata":{"content":"The result is **Static MCP** — *your tools are files, not servers*: skills published as static, hash-verified content and executed sandboxed on demand. What static site hosting did to web servers (\"do not run Apache, publish HTML\"), this does to MCP servers: the publisher runs no infrastructure at all; the MCP server is materialized per request from the published files and evaporates after responding (ephemeral instance, durable definition).","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-3","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-1-motivation-3#0","metadata":{"content":"1. **Age is a proxy, not truth.** Whether code is still trustworthy is a human judgment; the only honest way to capture it is a human signature with an explicit validity window. Nothing here pretends to automate that judgment. 2. **Zero infrastructure, like everything else in this standard.** Attestations are static JSON files. No transparency log, no CA, no server.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-1-motivation-3","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-16#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Advisory** (default): all verified skills load; the verdict is exposed to the consumer (e.g. in the tool description or a discovery diagnostic) so agents/operators can decide. - **Enforcing**: only `attested` skills load; everything else is excluded like a hash mismatch.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-16","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 4. Runtime behavior"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-2#0","metadata":{"content":"This extension closes that gap for publishers who want it: a skill MAY additionally ship an **executable artifact** — a small JavaScript file with a declared input schema — that a conforming runtime executes *verbatim* inside a sandbox, instead of asking a model to improvise from prose.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-development-notes-22#0","metadata":{"content":"- `TAREA4-REPORT.md` — deploying to Cloudflare Workers: the `CompiledWasm` rule and why importing the `.wasm` as a static module avoids \"Wasm code generation disallowed by embedder\". - `TAREA5-REPORT.md` — the asyncify spike: why asyncify is needed for an `await`-shaped capability, and the promise-pumping loop in `AsyncToolHost.callTool`. - `TAREA7-REPORT.md` — the gateway: sha256 verification, the Cache API use, and the Cloudflare error 1042 (same-account worker-to-worker fetch via `workers.dev`) workaround via a service binding.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-development-notes-22","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Development notes"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-78#0","metadata":{"content":"The skill was treated as \"interesting documentation\" rather than as a \"behavioral contract\" that overrides the agent's default tools. The API call succeeded, but the agent did not follow the skill's intent: it used different tooling, different error handling, and different conventions than those the site designed.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-78","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.3 Observed Execution Gap"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-24#0","metadata":{"content":"*Example:* `img.automators.work` teaches agents to call `/{width}x{height}?bg={hex}` to generate placeholder images.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-24","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.4 Two primary use cases"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-2-2-signing-payload-6#0","metadata":{"content":"The signature covers the UTF-8 bytes of the canonical string:","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-2-2-signing-payload-6","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 2.2 Signing payload"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-9#0","metadata":{"content":"Under a `## Skills` section, an executable skill is a normal markdown list item followed by an HTML comment carrying a JSON object with `version`, `tool` (path to the `tool.js`), and `tool_sha256` (hex SHA-256 of the `tool.js` bytes):","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-9","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: The executable-skill line in `llms.txt`"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-8-open-questions-88#0","metadata":{"content":"1. **Should `llms.txt` grow parallel `## MCP` and `## Agents` sections**, making it the single discovery document for a domain's full agent surface? Or should each standard manage its own discovery separately? 2. **Cross-origin skill trust model.** Should cross-origin skills be disallowed entirely, allowed with elevated confirmation, or allowed freely? Current proposal: allowed with elevated confirmation (§4.4). 3. **Archive format.** Should `.zip` be the only mandated archive format, or should `.tar.gz` remain in scope? `.zip` is more universally supported; `.tar.gz` is more natural for git-hosted skill bundles. 4.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-8-open-questions-88","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 8. Open Questions"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-2-relationship-to-agents-txt-the-actio-34#0","metadata":{"content":"**[agents.txt](https://agents-txt.com).** A capability-declaration file (`/agents.txt` + optional `/agents.json`) that advertises which agent-facing protocols a site supports — payments (x402, MPP, AP2), authorization (agent-auth, OAuth2), MCP, A2A, UCP, WebMCP, and **Skills**. It positions itself as \"Layer 4 (action)\" above `robots.txt` (access) and `llms.txt` (content). Its `Skills:` directive and its `/.well-known/agent-skills/index.json` both build on the [Agent Skills](https://agentskills.io) `discovery/0.2.0` index schema.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-2-relationship-to-agents-txt-the-actio-34","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.2 Relationship to `agents.txt` (the action layer)"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-3-versioning-and-updates-13#0","metadata":{"content":"The `tool_sha256` pins the artifact. Publishing a new artifact version means serving new bytes at `tool` and updating both `tool_sha256` and `version` in `llms.txt`. Runtimes cache by hash; a stale hash simply keeps serving the old, verified artifact until the index updates.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-3-versioning-and-updates-13","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.3 Versioning and updates"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-security-model-honest-19#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Auth is a single shared bearer token, optional by config.** If the `AUTH_TOKEN` secret is set, the gateway requires `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on `POST /mcp` (401 otherwise); the deployed gateway has it enabled. Without the secret it runs open (dev mode). There is still no per-client identity or rate limiting. The PoC worker remains open. - **Per-skill isolation is context-level, not process-level.** Skills get separate QuickJS contexts but share the same wasm module instance and the same Worker request; the boundary is the QuickJS API surface, not an OS process. - **One asyncify suspension at a time.** QuickJS asyncify suspends/resumes a single stack; concurrent overlapping async capabilities are not supported. - **State is in-memory and per-request.** No persistence, no warm sta","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-security-model-honest-19","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Security model (honest)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-3-the-well-known-convention-is-limited-11#0","metadata":{"content":"**Co-location matters.** An agent that reads `llms.txt` to understand a site already has the right document open. If skill discovery requires a separate probe, that is extra latency and a second source of truth.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-3-the-well-known-convention-is-limited-11","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.3 The well-known convention is limited"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-2-3-publication-9#0","metadata":{"content":"(consistent with the core RFC's `/.well-known/agent-skills/index.json` metadata layer). Multiple attestations per skill (different reviewers) are allowed and encouraged. Third-party reviewers MAY additionally publish their attestations on their own domain; how runtimes discover those is an open question (§6).","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-2-3-publication-9","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 2.3 Publication"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-38#0","metadata":{"content":"A growing body of work attacks **tool-definition bloat** — the cost of injecting every tool's schema into the model context up front. It comes in two camps:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-38","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-2-1-the-attestation-object-5#0","metadata":{"content":"| Field | Requirement | Meaning | |---|---|---| | `origin` | REQUIRED | The publishing origin the review applies to. | | `skill` | REQUIRED | Skill name as it appears in `llms.txt`. | | `tool_sha256` | REQUIRED | The exact artifact hash reviewed. A new artifact version voids the attestation by construction. | | `attester` | REQUIRED | Reviewer identity, `<type>:<name>` (e.g. `human:mauricio`). | | `signed_on` / `valid_until` | REQUIRED | Validity window, `YYYY-MM-DD` in UTC. An attestation is EXPIRED when the current UTC date is strictly greater than `valid_until` (the end date is inclusive). | | `signature` | REQUIRED | Ed25519 over the signing payload (§2.2), **base64** (aligned with the core RFC tooling, `scripts/verify_signatures.py`).","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-2-1-the-attestation-object-5","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 2.1 The attestation object"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-3-reviewer-registry-trust-anchor-11#0","metadata":{"content":"Runtimes MAY populate it by explicit configuration (recommended) or TOFU-pin keys on first sight (consistent with core RFC §4.6). An attestation from an unknown attester verifies as UNKNOWN-ATTESTER, not as valid.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-3-reviewer-registry-trust-anchor-11","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 3. Reviewer registry (trust anchor)"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-why-4#0","metadata":{"content":"MCP clients (Claude, Cursor, others) can call arbitrary tools. Running a third-party tool's code directly in your backend means that code can read your secrets, hit your DB, phone home, or loop forever. You either trust the author fully or you don't run the tool.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-why-4","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Why"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-2-recommended-agent-behavior-non-norma-73#0","metadata":{"content":"When an agent runtime decides to implement proactive discovery, this is the recommended flow:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-2-recommended-agent-behavior-non-norma-73","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.2 Recommended Agent Behavior (Non-Normative)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-79#0","metadata":{"content":"**Why this happens:** - Agent runtimes do not have a \"skill execution mode\" that suspends generic tools and forces compliance with a downloaded `SKILL.md`. - Skills are not sandboxed or enforced; they are suggestions that the model may or may not follow. - The reward function of the agent (\"complete the user's task\") does not penalize tool substitution if the outcome is similar.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-79","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.3 Observed Execution Gap"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-3-discovery-flow-22#0","metadata":{"content":"Step 5 is mandatory. Agents MUST NOT auto-install or auto-activate skills without explicit user approval (see §4).","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-3-discovery-flow-22","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.3 Discovery flow"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-2-optional-inline-metadata-19#0","metadata":{"content":"A skill entry MAY carry a version hint as a trailing HTML comment:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-2-optional-inline-metadata-19","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.2 Optional inline metadata"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-66#0","metadata":{"content":"**Limitation:** DNS TXT records are limited to ~255 bytes per string and require DNS access, which sandboxed agents may not have.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-66","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-5-security-considerations-18#0","metadata":{"content":"- **What this buys:** an agent operator can require \"code reviewed by someone I chose, endorsement not expired\" before executing third-party artifacts. Compromising the publisher's site is no longer enough to ship malicious code to enforcing runtimes — the attacker also needs a registered reviewer's private key. - **What this does not buy:** a review is a point-in-time human judgment; it cannot guarantee the absence of vulnerabilities. Key compromise of a reviewer defeats the ring for that reviewer's attestations (mitigation: multiple reviewers, short windows). Revocation before `valid_until` is unsolved here (§6) — short validity windows are the honest stopgap.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-5-security-considerations-18","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 5. Security considerations"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-7-changelog-26#0","metadata":{"content":"- **v0.4 (2026-07-02):** Origin memory (§2.4): hash-pinned search snapshots (`skills-memory` line, `snapshot_sha256`, pluggable `format`) and the origin-scoped `host.memorySearch` capability; runtime requirement for snapshot integrity. Field-tested: the reference gateway serves BM25 search over the spec's own docs published as a static snapshot (`minimemory-okf-v1`).","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-7-changelog-26","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 7. Changelog"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-59#0","metadata":{"content":"As agent runtimes evolve toward more proactive web discovery, the `## Skills` section provides the declaration primitive those systems will need.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-59","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5. On Agent-Side Discovery Triggers"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-63#0","metadata":{"content":"**Reference implementation:** [DemoShop](https://demoshop-88e.pages.dev) sends this header on every API response.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-63","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-ecosystem-comparison-28#0","metadata":{"content":"| Dimension | MCP | A2A | `/.well-known/skills/` | **`## Skills` in `llms.txt`** | |---|---|---|---|---| | Requires server process | Yes | Yes | **No** | **No** | | Works on static hosts | No | No | **Yes** | **Yes** | | Multi-skill per domain | Yes | Yes | **No** (fixed path) | **Yes** | | Co-located with `llms.txt` | No | No | No | **Yes** | | Zero infrastructure beyond static files | No | No | **Yes** | **Yes** | | Complex / stateful integrations | **Yes** | **Yes** | No | No | | Simple API wrapping | Overkill | Overkill | Limited | **Designed for this** | | Version metadata inline | N/A | N/A | No | **Yes** | | User opt-in required | Runtime-dependent | Runtime-dependent | Runtime-dependent | **Mandatory** |","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-ecosystem-comparison-28","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3. Ecosystem Comparison"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-56#0","metadata":{"content":"Today, most agents read `llms.txt` only when the user explicitly directs them to a URL or instructs them to research a site. Proactive, background skill discovery does not yet occur in mainstream runtimes.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-56","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5. On Agent-Side Discovery Triggers"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-43#0","metadata":{"content":"**Evidence (reference POC, [`evals/poc_orchestration/`](../evals/poc_orchestration/README.md)).** Against a live n8n MCP server (which exposes **25 tools** to build a workflow), a small local model was driven through a real agentic loop in five arms spanning *how much capability sits in context as tool schemas vs. as skill prose*:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-43","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-71#0","metadata":{"content":"**Why it matters:** It requires zero cooperation from the site (the file either exists or it doesn't). It costs one cheap HEAD request (~200 bytes). It works for every domain on the web, not just those that implement headers or DNS records.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-71","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-51#0","metadata":{"content":"**What the signature actually buys you.** Publishing the public key on the same origin does not, by itself, defeat a fully compromised origin: an attacker who controls the server can swap key, signatures, and content together. The value is:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-51","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 4.6 Signing and authenticity (resolves Open Question 4)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-31#0","metadata":{"content":"**[auth.md](https://github.com/workos/auth.md) (WorkOS).** A protocol where a service hosts an `AUTH.md` describing how an agent can register and authenticate on the user's behalf, discovered via `/.well-known/oauth-authorization-server` metadata. It is **complementary, not competing**, with this RFC:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-31","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.1 Relationship to adjacent protocols"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-9-reference-implementation-91#0","metadata":{"content":"[`img.automators.work`](https://img.automators.work) is a live Cloudflare Pages static site — no server process, no MCP server, no A2A endpoint.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-9-reference-implementation-91","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 9. Reference Implementation"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-proposal-16#0","metadata":{"content":"Add an optional `## Skills` section to `llms.txt`. Each entry is a link to a remote `SKILL.md` (or a skill bundle archive) that conforms to the Agent Skills spec.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-proposal-16","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2. Proposal"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-40#0","metadata":{"content":"**This RFC is complementary, and sits at a third place: publisher-side, and one level up.** Two differences matter:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-40","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-15#0","metadata":{"content":"Call `sum_numbers` (pure sync tool, runs in the sandbox):","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-15","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-3-runtime-requirements-19#0","metadata":{"content":"A runtime that executes skills published under this extension (a *gateway*, an agent-embedded engine, etc.):","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-3-runtime-requirements-19","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 3. Runtime requirements"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-32#1","metadata":{"content":"5). The two `.well-known` documents can coexist. - **Terminology overlap.** `auth.md` uses the word \"skill\" for its auth manifest, distinct from an [Agent Skills](https:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-32","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.1 Relationship to adjacent protocols"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-quick-start-11#0","metadata":{"content":"Requirements: Node 18+ and `npm install` (already done in this checkout).","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-quick-start-11","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Quick start"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-46#0","metadata":{"content":"This is the same pattern already live on the reference site **[demoshop](https://demoshop-88e.pages.dev)**, whose skills (`product-search`, `cart-add`) teach an agent to call one REST endpoint directly — zero tools in context — for *simple* capabilities. The n8n POC shows the pattern **scales to a complex, tool-heavy capability**, and maps the cost of each rung.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-46","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-69#0","metadata":{"content":"#### Mechanism D — The `/llms.txt` convention probe","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-69","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-52#0","metadata":{"content":"1. **Offline key.** Because the private key is not on the server, a server compromise *alone* (without the key) cannot forge valid signatures. The attacker can only serve unsigned or invalid-signature content, which a verifying agent rejects. 2. **Agent-side key pinning (TOFU).** The agent pins the origin's public key on first use and warns / requires re-confirmation if it later changes. This detects silent key or skill swaps across sessions — the gap that plain `sha256` cannot close.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-52","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 4.6 Signing and authenticity (resolves Open Question 4)"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-5-reference-implementation-23#0","metadata":{"content":"| Piece | URL | |---|---| | Runtime + gateway source (QuickJS-wasm sandbox on Cloudflare Workers) | https://github.com/MauricioPerera/mcpwasm | | Demo publishing site (`llms.txt` with two executable skills) | https://llmstxt-demo-site.rckflr.workers.dev/llms.txt | | Realistic publisher (D1-backed bookstore: search/detail/stock/**order** skills, plus permanent robustness fixtures: a deliberately hash-mismatched skill and an infinite-loop skill) | https://llmstxt-bookstore.rckflr.workers.dev/llms.txt | | Docs publisher (the standard's own docs, searchable via a hash-pinned BM25 snapshot + `search_spec` skill — the spec searches itself) | https://llmstxt-docs.rckflr.workers.dev/llms.txt | | Gateway exposing them as an MCP server | `POST https://llmstxt-gateway.rckflr.workers.dev/mcp?origin=","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-5-reference-implementation-23","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 5. Reference implementation"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-41#0","metadata":{"content":"1. **Search finds; a skill *prescribes*.** Tool search reduces the token cost of *having* many tools, but it does not tell the agent the *order* to use them in, the dependencies, or what to do on error — the agent must still formulate a query (a cold-start problem) and discover the procedure, sometimes by failing. A published skill carries the **recipe**: the procedure at the level of intent. (n8n's own MCP concedes this — it ships an `instructions` blob telling the agent the call order, because the tool list alone is insufficient.) 2. **Trust + curation.** None of the above says *who* published a capability or verifies it; this RFC adds offline-key signatures + pinning (§4.6) and a human-curated procedure tier.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-41","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-8-open-questions-90#0","metadata":{"content":"URLs in `## Skills` MAY mirror those already declared in `.well-known/agent-skills/index.json`, reusing the same artifacts without duplication. Agents that support both get redundant coverage at zero extra cost for publishers.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-8-open-questions-90","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 8. Open Questions"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-3-the-well-known-convention-is-limited-10#0","metadata":{"content":"It fails when: - The site wants to declare **multiple** skills for different use cases. - The agent encounters the site for the first time via `llms.txt`. - The site wants to co-locate skill discovery with the rest of its agent-facing context.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-3-the-well-known-convention-is-limited-10","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.3 The well-known convention is limited"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-4-why-structured-over-prose-14#0","metadata":{"content":"- **LLM-free parsing.** A regex parser can extract `## Skills` entries without invoking a model. Prose requires inference to normalize (\"here's a skill:\", \"you can use:\", \"for API access:\") — every site phrases it differently. - **Non-LLM tooling.** Validators, CI linters, skill crawlers, and IDE integrations need a fixed schema to function. Prose is unparseable without a model in the loop. - **Runtime auto-discovery.** An agent runtime can implement native `## Skills` support with a deterministic code path. With prose, the runtime needs per-site prompt engineering to extract the same signal. - **Cross-domain indexing.** A skills directory can index published skills across all domains by crawling `## Skills` sections. This is not possible with ad-hoc prose.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-4-why-structured-over-prose-14","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.4 Why structured over prose"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-4#0","metadata":{"content":"Executing third-party code is only acceptable under a strict security model. This extension therefore defines two things, and only two things:","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-4","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-2-relationship-to-agents-txt-the-actio-36#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Discovery surface.** `agents.txt` answers *\"which capability families does this site expose?\"* across many protocols at once; `## Skills` in `llms.txt` is the co-located, content-adjacent surface for the Skills family specifically. A site can serve both: a `Skills:` line in `agents.txt` and a `## Skills` section in `llms.txt`, pointing at the **same** `SKILL.md` artifacts. - **Trust.** `agents.txt`'s Skills layer carries discovery and integrity (`digest`) but **explicitly leaves authenticity out** (\"prioritize discovery simplicity over trust verification\"). That is exactly the gap this RFC's Tier 2 closes (§4.6): offline-key ed25519 signatures + agent-side key pinning. The two stack cleanly — `agents.txt`/agentskills.io for discovery and integrity, this RFC for authenticity.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-2-relationship-to-agents-txt-the-actio-36","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.2 Relationship to `agents.txt` (the action layer)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-57#0","metadata":{"content":"This is not a defect of the proposal — it is the current state of the ecosystem. MCP, A2A, and `/.well-known/skills/` face the same trigger problem: all require the user or agent to know the site exists before discovery begins.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-on-agent-side-discovery-triggers-57","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5. On Agent-Side Discovery Triggers"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-84#0","metadata":{"content":"**Why this happens:** - The agent interpreted the URL as a decorative reference, not as a service endpoint. - The runtime has no rule that says: \"when a user mentions a domain, check `/llms.txt` before acting.\" - The default behavior is \"do what the user asked with local tools\" rather than \"delegate to the domain's published skills.\"","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-84","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.4 Discovery from User Instructions"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-1-skill-entry-10#0","metadata":{"content":"Rationale for staying inline (rather than only in `/.well-known/agent-skills/index.json`): the core standard's value proposition is *one static file, no infrastructure*. Two inline keys preserve that. Publishers who already maintain the well-known index MAY mirror the same `tool`/`tool_sha256` fields there; if both are present and disagree, runtimes MUST refuse the skill.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-1-skill-entry-10","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.1 Skill entry"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-5-reference-implementation-23#1","metadata":{"content":"s://llmstxt-gateway.rckflr.workers.dev/mcp?origin=<u","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-5-reference-implementation-23","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 5. Reference implementation"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-15#0","metadata":{"content":"Runtimes SHOULD support at least two modes:","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-15","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 4. Runtime behavior"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-1-motivation-4#0","metadata":{"content":"This layer is **OPTIONAL**. Publishers who skip it lose nothing they have today; runtimes decide what unattested skills are worth.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-1-motivation-4","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-mcpwasm-static-mcp-3#0","metadata":{"content":"This repo integrates with the [llms-txt-skills](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/llms-txt-skills) standard via a provisional extension for executable skills (see below).","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-mcpwasm-static-mcp-3","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-repository-layout-20#0","metadata":{"content":"| File / dir | Purpose | |---|---| | `host.mjs` | Synchronous `ToolHost`: loads `tool.js` into QuickJS-wasm, injects the `host.callInternal` capability. | | `host-async.mjs` | `AsyncToolHost`: asyncify variant, async handlers, `host.fetchOrigin` capability, mem/stack/interrupt hardening. | | `mcp-core.mjs` | Sync MCP JSON-RPC 2.0 core (`initialize`, `tools/list`, `tools/call`, `ping`). Transport-agnostic. | | `mcp-core-async.mjs` | Async MCP core; awaits `AsyncToolHost.callTool`. | | `worker.mjs` | PoC MCP server (sync host, inline tools) deployed at `toolhost-mcp.rckflr.workers.dev`. | | `worker-spike.mjs` | Async spike (fetch_home/fetch_evil) proving origin-scoped fetch. | | `worker-gateway.mjs` | The gateway: discover → verify → load → serve MCP.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-repository-layout-20","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Repository layout"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-60#0","metadata":{"content":"To reduce the friction of skill discovery from \"user must know to ask\" to \"agent finds it automatically\", this RFC proposes four optional mechanisms that sites MAY implement and agents MAY support. None are required for compliance, but each lowers the barrier for the agent side.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-60","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-83#0","metadata":{"content":"The agent: 1. Did not fetch `https://img.automators.work/llms.txt`. 2. Did not discover the `placeholder` skill. 3. Did not learn that the site generates SVG placeholder images via `/600x50?bg=22c55e`. 4. Instead, created a local PNG with Python/PIL, ignoring the URL entirely.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-83","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.4 Discovery from User Instructions"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-44#0","metadata":{"content":"| arm | tool defs in context | result | |---|---:|---| | raw MCP (n8n's own setup) | 25 | at a 4k context, the tools **do not even fit** (overflow before turn 1) | | skill + declared tool segment | 8 | runs; same task, −68% tool surface | | skill + 1 generic MCP passthrough | **1** | runs the full recipe, keeps node introspection | | skill + 1 generic HTTP tool (REST, no MCP) | **1** | builds and `POST`s the workflow in a single call |","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-44","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-2-existing-alternatives-require-infras-7#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Static sites** (Cloudflare Pages, GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel) — no server process exists. - **Existing APIs** that want to teach agents which endpoints to call, not reimplement their surface. - **Documentation sites** that want to describe interaction patterns once, not maintain a daemon.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-2-existing-alternatives-require-infras-7","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.2 Existing alternatives require infrastructure most sites do not have"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-2-2-signing-payload-7#0","metadata":{"content":"**`origin` is deliberately inside the payload.** Identical bytes on a different origin are a *different skill in effect*: `fetchOrigin` is scoped to the publishing origin, so the same code talks to a different backend. An attestation MUST NOT be replayable across origins. (This is the one place this extension diverges from the donor PoC, which had no cross-site dimension.)","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-2-2-signing-payload-7","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 2.2 Signing payload"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-10-changelog-93#0","metadata":{"content":"- **v0.8 (2026-06-02):** Extended §3.3 with the `n8n-skills-sdk` companion experiment — reproducing the n8n MCP's build path entirely with a published skill + `@n8n/workflow-sdk` (local parse/validate) + the REST API (no MCP): a local model builds+validates+creates the same workflows in ~3 tool calls (vs the MCP's 6–7), validation preserved, 3 tool defs in context; cross-model (8–9B succeed, 3B hits a code-writing floor).","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-10-changelog-93","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 10. Changelog"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-13#0","metadata":{"content":"The gateway is live at `https://llmstxt-gateway.rckflr.workers.dev`. It is restricted to origins in its allowlist; the demo site `https://llmstxt-demo-site.rckflr.workers.dev` and the bookstore `https://llmstxt-bookstore.rckflr.workers.dev` (D1-backed, includes a write skill `create_order`) are allowed. `origin` is URL-encoded as a query param. The deployed gateway requires `-H \"Authorization: Bearer <token>\"` on every request below (auth is optional by config; see the security model).","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-13","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-repository-layout-20#1","metadata":{"content":"eway: discover → verify → load → serve MCP. Deployed at `llmstxt-gateway.rckflr.work","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-repository-layout-20","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Repository layout"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-39#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Model/client-side.** Anthropic's [Tool Search Tool](https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/agents-and-tools/tool-use/tool-search-tool) (`defer_loading`) loads only the few relevant tools on demand (reported ~85% fewer tool-definition tokens). Tool-retrieval / \"tool RAG\" (LangChain toolkits, Gorilla) does the same via embeddings. - **Server-side.** The MCP [progressive-disclosure SEP](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/modelcontextprotocol/issues/1888) proposes a server capability that exposes one meta-tool with `searchTools` modes instead of registering hundreds.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-39","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-47#0","metadata":{"content":"**Reproducing the server, not just shrinking it.** A companion experiment ([`n8n-skills-sdk`](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/n8n-skills-sdk)) takes the last rung — *no MCP at all*. The n8n MCP's build path turns out to be a thin wrapper over the [`@n8n/workflow-sdk`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@n8n/workflow-sdk) package (local code→JSON parse + `validateWorkflow`) plus one REST call (`POST /workflows`): `get_sdk_reference`, `validate_workflow`, and `create_workflow_from_code` map onto the package's own exports and the public API. Delivered as a published `SKILL.md` + three local tools (`reference`/`validate`/`create`), a local model built, validated, and created the same workflows the MCP does — in **~3 tool calls vs.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-47","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-42#0","metadata":{"content":"So `llms.txt` Skills can be the **server-less catalog** these consumer-side mechanisms need a source for — Tool Search needs a catalog; the SEP needs the server to implement it; a `## Skills` section is that catalog, owned by the domain, with the recipe and the signature attached.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-42","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-53#0","metadata":{"content":"**Higher assurance.** For identity-bound provenance, publishers SHOULD consider **keyless signing via a transparency log** (e.g., Sigstore): the artifact is signed by an OIDC identity — such as the CI workflow that built it — and recorded in a public log, so verification asserts *who* produced the artifact, not merely that *some* key did. Trade-off: verification needs network access to the transparency log, which sandboxed agents may lack; same-origin ed25519 + pinning works fully offline.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-53","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 4.6 Signing and authenticity (resolves Open Question 4)"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-extension-skill-attestations-0#0","metadata":{"content":"**Status:** Draft (v0.2) **Date:** 2026-07-02 **Extends:** [Extension: Executable Skills](./ext-executable-skills.md) (v0.3) **Design donor:** the three-layer knowledge-governance PoC in [ccdd/examples/okf-integration](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/ccdd/tree/main/examples/okf-integration) (working Ed25519 attestation + freshness tooling), adapted here to executable skills.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-extension-skill-attestations-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: Extension: Skill Attestations"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-1-motivation-1#0","metadata":{"content":"The executable-skills extension gives two rings of trust: `tool_sha256` proves **integrity** (these bytes are these bytes) and core RFC §4.6 signatures prove **authenticity** (the publisher signed them). Neither answers the question an agent operator actually cares about before running third-party code: **has a human I trust reviewed this code, and do they still stand behind it?** A correctly hashed, correctly signed malicious artifact passes both rings — the residual risk §4 of the executable-skills extension explicitly admits.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-1-motivation-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-7-changelog-20#0","metadata":{"content":"- **v0.2 (2026-07-02):** Review fixes: base64 encoding for signatures/keys (aligned with core RFC tooling), canonical-origin and date normalization rules for the signing payload, inclusive-end UTC expiry semantics, and explicit verdict precedence (invalid dominates). - **v0.1 (2026-07-02):** Initial draft, adapted from the ccdd okf-integration PoC (Ed25519 attestations + freshness windows + key registry), with origin-binding added for the cross-site skill context.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-7-changelog-20","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 7. Changelog"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-extension-executable-skills-0#0","metadata":{"content":"**Status:** Draft (v0.4) **Date:** 2026-07-02 **Extends:** [RFC: Publishing Agent Skills through `llms.txt`](./rfc-skills-in-llms-txt.md) (v0.8)","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-extension-executable-skills-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: Extension: Executable Skills"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-1#0","metadata":{"content":"The core RFC publishes skills as instructional documents (`SKILL.md`). Section 5.3 of the core RFC identifies the *execution gap*: an agent may read instructions and still improvise, substitute tools, or drift from the published behavior.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-security-48#0","metadata":{"content":"1. **No auto-installation.** Agents MUST NOT activate a discovered skill without explicit user opt-in. 2. **Same-origin preference.** Agents SHOULD treat same-origin skills as lower friction than cross-origin skills. 3. **Content verification.** If `sha256` is declared in the inline metadata, agents MUST verify the hash of the fetched file and refuse to load on mismatch. 4. **Cross-origin skills require elevated confirmation.** If a skill URL is on a different origin from the `llms.txt` that references it, agents SHOULD require additional user confirmation beyond the base opt-in. This prevents a compromised `llms.txt` from silently delegating trust to a third-party host. 5. **Least privilege.** Skills loaded from a domain operate within the permission scope of that domain. They cannot requ","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-security-48","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 4. Security"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-12#0","metadata":{"content":"A runtime that supports this extension evaluates, per skill, at discovery time:","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-12","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 4. Runtime behavior"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-skills-18#0","metadata":{"content":"1. The section heading MUST be exactly `## Skills` (case-insensitive). 2. Each list item MUST follow the standard `llms.txt` link convention: `- [title](URL): description`. 3. The URL MUST resolve to either: - A raw `SKILL.md` document (`Content-Type: text/markdown`), OR - An archive ending in `.zip` or `.tar.gz` containing `SKILL.md` at the archive root. 4. The remote `SKILL.md` MUST be a valid Agent Skill (YAML frontmatter + body per the Agent Skills spec). 5. The URL SHOULD be same-origin as the `llms.txt`. Cross-origin URLs are permitted but carry additional security implications (see §4). 6. The description SHOULD match or summarize the `description` field in the skill's frontmatter.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-skills-18","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: Skills"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-4-why-structured-over-prose-15#0","metadata":{"content":"The structure adds zero friction for publishers (two lines of markdown) and enables the tooling layer above it.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-4-why-structured-over-prose-15","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.4 Why structured over prose"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-development-notes-21#0","metadata":{"content":"Each milestone is documented in its `TAREA*-REPORT.md`. The non-obvious bits live there:","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-development-notes-21","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Development notes"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-8-open-questions-89#0","metadata":{"content":"| Layer | Mechanism | Role | |---|---|---| | Discovery | `## Skills` in `llms.txt` | Passive, co-located with domain context; zero extra fetch | | Metadata & verification | `.well-known/agent-skills/index.json` | sha256, version, license, cost estimates | | Active install | `.well-known/skills/default/skill.md` | Single-skill convention probe |","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-8-open-questions-89","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 8. Open Questions"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-17#0","metadata":{"content":"- `await host.memorySearch(query, k?)` -> `{ hits: [{ text, score, title, concept_id }] }` — BM25 search over the origin's own snapshot. `query` MUST be a string; `k` is capped by the runtime (reference implementation: 10). Like `fetchOrigin`, the capability is strictly origin-scoped: a skill can only search the snapshot its own publisher shipped. Skills SHOULD check for the capability before calling it (`typeof host.memorySearch === \"function\"`) — it is absent when the runtime does not support the declared format or when verification fails.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-17","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.4 Origin memory: search snapshots"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-23#0","metadata":{"content":"**Pattern A — API wrapping.** The site has a public HTTP API. The skill teaches the agent how to authenticate and which endpoints to call. The agent executes calls directly against the API.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-23","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.4 Two primary use cases"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-45#0","metadata":{"content":"The same workflow gets built with **one tool definition in context instead of 25**. The decisive, model-independent result is the 4k overflow: the raw tool list is *unusable* on a small model, while a skill's declared segment is not. (Honest scoping: once the tools *fit*, the orchestration gap among the MCP arms is marginal on an easy task with a capable model; and the leanest REST arm trades the SDK's parameter validation for speed. It is a single-model POC, not a benchmark — see its README.)","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-3-skills-as-the-recipe-layer-over-tool-45","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.3 Skills as the *recipe* layer over tool discovery"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-64#0","metadata":{"content":"The domain MAY publish a DNS TXT record:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-64","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-32#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Different layer.** `auth.md` answers *\"how does an agent authenticate to this service?\"*; `## Skills` answers *\"what can an agent do here, and how?\"*. This RFC's example skills are deliberately auth-free; `auth.md` is exactly the missing authentication layer. A fully agent-ready domain can serve **both**: `## Skills` for capability discovery and `AUTH.md` for credential acquisition. - **Discovery alignment.** `auth.md` is discovered through a `.well-known` pointer that carries a `skill` field referencing the manifest — the same shape as this RFC's `/.well-known/agent-skills/index.json` metadata layer (§8, Open Question 5). The two `.well-known` documents can coexist.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-1-relationship-to-adjacent-protocols-32","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.1 Relationship to adjacent protocols"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-70#0","metadata":{"content":"Similar to `robots.txt` or `favicon.ico`, agents MAY adopt the convention:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-70","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-1-skill-entry-8#0","metadata":{"content":"| Key | Type | Requirement | Meaning | |----------|--------|-------------|---------| | `version`| string | inherited from core RFC | Human-readable hint. | | `tool` | string | REQUIRED for executable skills | Path to the executable artifact. MUST be a same-origin path (relative or absolute path, never a full URL to another origin). | | `tool_sha256` | string | REQUIRED when `tool` is present | Lowercase hex SHA-256 of the exact bytes served at `tool`. |","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-1-skill-entry-8","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.1 Skill entry"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-3-runtime-requirements-20#0","metadata":{"content":"1. **Integrity.** MUST fetch the artifact, compute SHA-256 over the exact received bytes, and compare with the declared `tool_sha256`. On mismatch the skill MUST be excluded (not degraded to prose, not executed) and the rejection SHOULD be observable (log or diagnostic surface). This matches the mandatory-refusal language of core RFC §4. 2. **Isolation.** MUST execute artifacts in a sandbox where the host environment is not reachable: no ambient network, no filesystem, no host secrets. Host capabilities are injected explicitly; this extension defines only `host.fetchOrigin`, scoped to the publishing origin. A runtime MUST reject any `fetchOrigin` target that resolves outside that origin. 3.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-3-runtime-requirements-20","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 3. Runtime requirements"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-why-5#0","metadata":{"content":"mcpwasm removes the trust requirement for the *code*:","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-why-5","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Why"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-development-notes-23#0","metadata":{"content":"Run the e2e tests with `npm test` (sync) / `npm run spike` (async) / `npm run gateway` (gateway against the live demo site).","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-development-notes-23","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: Development notes"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-49#0","metadata":{"content":"**Threat model.** A `sha256` declared in `## Skills` or in `index.json` provides **integrity** — the content was not corrupted in transit or by a CDN. It does **not** provide **authenticity**, because the same document that points to the skill also asserts its hash. A party that can modify the `llms.txt` or the index can rewrite the pointer and the hash together. Defending against a *compromised or malicious publisher* requires a signature whose trust is not rooted solely in the live document.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-4-6-signing-and-authenticity-resolves-op-49","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 4.6 Signing and authenticity (resolves Open Question 4)"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-2-1-the-attestation-object-5#1","metadata":{"content":"ore RFC tooling, `scripts/verify_signatures.py`). | | `note` | OPTIONAL | Human context; not part of","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-2-1-the-attestation-object-5","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 2.1 The attestation object"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-2-existing-alternatives-require-infras-6#0","metadata":{"content":"MCP and A2A are the right tools for complex, stateful integrations. They are overkill for:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-1-2-existing-alternatives-require-infras-6","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 1.2 Existing alternatives require infrastructure most sites do not have"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-18#0","metadata":{"content":"Updating content means re-exporting the snapshot and updating `snapshot_sha256` — same lifecycle as `tool_sha256` (§2.3).","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-4-origin-memory-search-snapshots-18","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.4 Origin memory: search snapshots"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-26#0","metadata":{"content":"**Pattern B — Interaction instructions.** The site has no dedicated API but wants to describe how an agent should interact with it. The skill contains heuristics, preferred phrasing, or task decomposition patterns.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-26","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.4 Two primary use cases"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-5-reference-implementation-22#0","metadata":{"content":"Working end-to-end chain (all deployed):","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-5-reference-implementation-22","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 5. Reference implementation"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-readme-the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-10#0","metadata":{"content":"- The `<!-- skill: {...} -->` comment marks the line as an *executable* skill. List items without it are treated as descriptive-only and ignored by the gateway. - `tool` is resolved relative to the origin. - `tool_sha256` is verified against the fetched `tool.js` bytes before the tool is loaded. Mismatch → the skill is rejected (logged) and not registered. - If the JSON is invalid the line is silently skipped (no throw).","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-readme-the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-10","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm-readme: The executable-skill line in `llms.txt`"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-ecosystem-comparison-29#0","metadata":{"content":"**This RFC does not replace MCP or A2A.** It fills the gap below them: the case where a site wants to publish a skill for a simple API or interaction pattern, without running a server.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-ecosystem-comparison-29","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3. Ecosystem Comparison"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-81#0","metadata":{"content":"A related but distinct gap occurs when the user includes a domain in their prompt, but the agent does not associate that URL with the need to discover skills.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-81","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.4 Discovery from User Instructions"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-67#0","metadata":{"content":"In addition to the existing `link rel=\"alternate\"`, the site MAY include a visible `<meta>` tag in the HTML `<head>`:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-1-proactive-discovery-mechanisms-67","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.1 Proactive Discovery Mechanisms"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-25#0","metadata":{"content":"*Example:* [DemoShop](https://demoshop-88e.pages.dev) publishes three skills (product-search, cart-add, checkout-complete) that teach agents to browse a catalog, add items to a cart, and complete a purchase via its public HTTP API — all without authentication or server-side sessions.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-2-4-two-primary-use-cases-25","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 2.4 Two primary use cases"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-2-2-the-artifact-tool-js-12#0","metadata":{"content":"- The file MUST call `registerTool(def)` exactly once, where `def.name` matches the skill name in `llms.txt`, `def.inputSchema` is a JSON Schema object, and `def.handler` is a function (sync or async). - The handler receives already-parsed `args` and returns a JSON-serializable value. Throwing reports a tool error to the caller; it MUST NOT crash the runtime. - The only ambient capability available is `host.fetchOrigin(path, opts?)`: an HTTP fetch **restricted to the publishing origin**, returning `{ status, body }` (body as text, possibly truncated by the runtime). Relative paths are resolved against the publishing origin. `opts` is optional: `{ method?: \"GET\" | \"POST\", body?: string, contentType?: string }`. The `method` defaults to `\"GET\"` if omitted. Only `GET` and `POST` are valid (an","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-2-2-the-artifact-tool-js-12","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 2.2 The artifact (`tool.js`)"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-6-open-questions-19#0","metadata":{"content":"1. Discovery of third-party attestations not hosted on the publishing origin (reviewer-side feeds? aggregators?). 2. Revocation before expiry (a static revocation list at the same well-known path is the zero-infra candidate). 3. Should `enforcing` mode distinguish per-capability risk (e.g. require attestation only for skills using POST)? 4. Alignment with core RFC §4.6: a signed `llms.txt` could pin `attestations.json` transitively.","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-6-open-questions-19","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 6. Open questions"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-2-relationship-to-agents-txt-the-actio-35#0","metadata":{"content":"This RFC and `agents.txt` are **complementary along two axes**:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-3-2-relationship-to-agents-txt-the-actio-35","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 3.2 Relationship to `agents.txt` (the action layer)"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-82#0","metadata":{"content":"**Empirical evidence from img.automators.work:** A user asked:","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-4-discovery-from-user-instructions-82","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.4 Discovery from User Instructions"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-skills-17#0","metadata":{"content":"- [skill-name](https://example.com/skills/skill-name/SKILL.md): description of when to use this skill. - [bundle-name](https://example.com/skills/bundle-name.zip): description. <!-- skill: {\"version\":\"1.0.0\"} --> ```","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-skills-17","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: Skills"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-6-why-this-is-worth-doing-86#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Deployable on any static host.** A Cloudflare Pages site, a GitHub Pages repo, a Netlify deploy — any host that can serve a text file can publish skills through this mechanism. No server process required. - **Self-describing at the source.** A site ships its API *and* the skill for consuming it in the same deploy. No third-party marketplace required. - **Version-locked to the API.** When the API changes, the skill changes in the same commit. No drift between capability and documentation. - **Co-located discovery.** An agent reading `llms.txt` finds skills in the same document, in one fetch, with no additional probing.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-6-why-this-is-worth-doing-86","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 6. Why This Is Worth Doing"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-6#0","metadata":{"content":"Everything else — transport, agent UX, approval flows — remains governed by the core RFC. A publisher that adopts this extension remains fully conformant with the core RFC: agents that do not understand executable skills simply fall back to `SKILL.md` prose.","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-1-motivation-6","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 1. Motivation"}},{"id":"ext-executable-skills-3-runtime-requirements-20#1","metadata":{"content":"gin` target that resolves outside that origin. 3. **Resource limits.** SHOULD enforce memory, stack, and execution budgets per invocation, so a hostil","okf_concept":"ext-executable-skills-3-runtime-requirements-20","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-executable-skills: 3. Runtime requirements"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-10-changelog-93#1","metadata":{"content":"l (8–9B succeed, 3B hits a code-writing floor). - **v0.7 (2026-06-02):** Added §3.3 \"Skills as the recipe layer over tool discovery\" positioning this RFC against tool-bloat work (Anthropic Tool Search / `defer_loading`, MCP progressive-disclosure SEP #1888, tool RAG) as the publisher-side, recipe-bearing layer those consumer/server-side mechanisms need a catalog for; added a reference POC (`evals/poc_orchestration/`) d","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-10-changelog-93","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 10. Changelog"}},{"id":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-76#0","metadata":{"content":"Discovery (Section 5) is only half the problem. Even when an agent successfully finds and reads a `SKILL.md`, there is no guarantee it will *execute* the skill according to its instructions.","okf_concept":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt-5-3-observed-execution-gap-76","okf_type":"docs","title":"rfc-skills-in-llms-txt: 5.3 Observed Execution Gap"}},{"id":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-13#0","metadata":{"content":"| Verdict | Condition | |---|---| | `attested` | ≥1 attestation with valid signature from a registered key, matching `origin`+`skill`+`tool_sha256`, within its validity window | | `expired` | matching attestations exist but all are past `valid_until` | | `invalid` | a signature fails verification (SHOULD be surfaced loudly — a forged attestation is worse than none) | | `unattested` | no matching attestation (including hash mismatch after a skill update) |","okf_concept":"ext-skill-attestations-4-runtime-behavior-13","okf_type":"docs","title":"ext-skill-attestations: 4. Runtime behavior"}}]